.TH man 3 "25 November 2025" "_printf manual" "Library Functions Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- custom implementation of the C standard printf function

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function writes formatted output to the standard output (file descriptor 1)
according to the format string provided.

Only a limited set of conversion specifiers is supported.
Characters that are not part of a valid format directive are printed as-is.

Supported conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string. If the string is NULL, the output is "(null)".

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed integer in decimal notation.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.

Unsupported format specifiers are printed literally (for example "%r" prints "%r").

.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.B _printf
function returns the total number of characters printed.
If an error occurs, a negative value is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following examples illustrate the expected output of
.B _printf
compared to normal execution:

.TP
.B _printf("Length:[%d, %i]\\n", len, len);
STDOUT: Length:[39, 39]

.TP
.B _printf("Negative:[%d]\\n", -762534);
STDOUT: Negative:[-762534]

.TP
.B _printf("Character:[%c]\\n", 'H');
STDOUT: Character:[H]

.TP
.B _printf("String:[%s]\\n", "I am a string !");
STDOUT: String:[I am a string !]

.TP
.B _printf("Percent:[%%]\\n");
STDOUT: Percent:[%]

.SH AUTHORS
Written by Aythan Cristovao, Vincent Renaud and auric chen.
